# STRATEGICLAND — Responsive System

> The same film must play on every screen.
> Mobile gets a **different cut** of the same film — shorter, simpler, equally emotional.
> Mobile is not "the desktop minus features". Mobile is **its own choreography**.

---

## 1. Responsive Philosophy

- The desktop experience is the **director's cut**. The mobile experience is the **theatrical cut**.
- Mobile preserves: typography weight, atmosphere, pacing, color, **emotional residue**.
- Mobile sacrifices: WebGL fidelity, custom cursor, magnetic interactions, horizontal pinning, deep parallax.
- The site is **built mobile-first** in its base styles, then enriched at desktop. Never the reverse.

---

## 2. Breakpoint System (LOCKED)

Tokens defined in Tailwind v4 `@theme`:

| Token        | Min width  | Device class            |
|--------------|-----------:|-------------------------|
| `xs`         | 0          | Mobile portrait         |
| `sm`         | 480px      | Mobile landscape, small phablets |
| `md`         | 768px      | Tablet portrait         |
| `lg`         | 1024px     | Tablet landscape / small laptop  |
| `xl`         | 1280px     | Desktop                 |
| `2xl`        | 1536px     | Large desktop           |
| `3xl`        | 1920px     | Cinematic desktop / 4K  |

### Constraints
- Use **6 breakpoints maximum**. Never invent intermediates.
- Layout shifts at `md` (768) and `lg` (1024) are the two most important — every chapter must be reviewed at exactly these widths.
- Cap effective viewport for hero `type.epic` at `3xl` (1920px) — beyond, type holds at the 240px ceiling and gutters expand.

---

## 3. Layout Adaptation per Breakpoint

| Aspect                  | xs / sm           | md                | lg / xl / 2xl              |
|-------------------------|-------------------|-------------------|----------------------------|
| Grid columns            | 4                 | 8                 | 12                         |
| Outer gutter            | 24px              | 48px              | 64–120px                   |
| Inter-column gutter     | 16px              | 24px              | 32px                       |
| Section vertical rhythm | 80vh              | 100vh             | 120vh                      |
| Display title alignment | left, full-bleed  | left, weighted    | off-center, golden ratio   |
| Image:text composition  | stacked           | stacked or side   | always side, asymmetric    |

---

## 4. Typography Scaling

Type tokens use `clamp()` to adapt smoothly. See `typography-system.mdc` for full scale.

### Constraints per breakpoint
- `xs`: body min **16px**. Display titles cap at **72px**.
- `md`: body **17px**. Display titles cap at **96px**.
- `lg+`: body **17px**. Display titles cap at **240px**.
- Tracking: tighten further at `lg+` (display gets `-0.04em`); body tracking remains stable across breakpoints.
- Leading: same tokens across breakpoints — `clamp()` handles size, not leading.

### Constraints
- Mobile must never wrap a `type.epic` into more than 3 lines.
- If a display title can't fit, **break the line manually**, never reduce font size below scale.

---

## 5. Motion Degradation

Motion is reduced as the device gets smaller, slower, or touch-only.

### 5.1 By breakpoint
| Feature                | xs / sm                  | md                       | lg+                       |
|------------------------|--------------------------|--------------------------|---------------------------|
| Lenis duration          | 1.2s (lighter)           | 1.4s                     | 1.4s                      |
| Reveal blur             | 0 (no blur entry)        | `BLUR.whisper` (2px)     | `BLUR.soft` (8px)         |
| Stagger                 | tight only               | editorial                | editorial / scene         |
| Parallax depth layers   | 1                        | 2                        | 3                         |
| Mouse-driven parallax   | disabled                 | disabled (no hover)      | enabled                   |
| Magnetic effects        | disabled                 | disabled                 | enabled                   |
| Custom cursor           | disabled                 | disabled                 | enabled                   |
| WebGL ambient           | disabled (CSS atmosphere)| optional                 | enabled                   |
| Image displacement (GLSL)| disabled                | disabled                 | enabled                   |

### 5.2 Detection
Use `gsap.matchMedia()` for branching timelines:
```ts
const mm = gsap.matchMedia();
mm.add({
  isDesktop: "(min-width: 1024px) and (pointer: fine)",
  isTablet: "(min-width: 768px) and (max-width: 1023px)",
  isMobile: "(max-width: 767px)",
  reduceMotion: "(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)",
}, (ctx) => {
  const { isDesktop, isMobile, reduceMotion } = ctx.conditions!;
  // build timelines conditionally
});
```

---

## 6. Horizontal Storytelling on Mobile

Horizontal pinning is **converted to vertical stacked layout** on `< md`.

### Conversion pattern
- Each "slide" of the horizontal track becomes a stacked vertical scene.
- Inter-slide transitions become individual vertical reveals (no pinning).
- The chapter retains its atmosphere and copy, just re-orchestrated linearly.
- Total scroll height on mobile is **shorter** than the equivalent desktop horizontal travel — mobile users scroll naturally faster.

### Constraints
- Never preserve horizontal scroll on touch devices — UX hostile.
- Never use CSS `overflow-x: scroll` for mobile fallback (browser scrollbar intrusion).
- Always test the converted vertical layout for narrative rhythm — it must still feel like a chapter.

---

## 7. Atmosphere on Mobile

- Grain: same opacity tokens, smaller texture (`grain-512.png`) to reduce memory.
- Vignette: same intensity (cheap CSS).
- Light leaks: reduced intensity (50% of desktop).
- WebGL ambient: **disabled by default** at `< md`. Re-enable opt-in per chapter if performance allows (FPS probe ≥ 50 for 1s).
- Atmospheric blur: cap at `BLUR.haze` (no `BLUR.veil` or `BLUR.fog` on mobile).

---

## 8. Touch-Specific Considerations

- Hover affordances must have **touch-equivalent affordances**: tap reveals the secondary state for 800ms.
- Tap targets: minimum **44×44 px** hitbox.
- Avoid hover-only content (tooltips, hover-revealed metadata) — replace with always-visible affordances on touch.
- Long-press gestures are **forbidden** (poor discoverability).
- Pull-to-refresh: disabled (`overscroll-behavior: none` on `<html>`).

---

## 9. Reduced Motion

`prefers-reduced-motion: reduce` is honored globally:
- Disable Lenis smoothing → native scroll.
- Disable all parallax, magnetic, cursor lerp, image displacement.
- Convert reveals to opacity-only, capped at `DUR.quick`.
- Disable WebGL drift (uniforms freeze at midpoint values).
- Disable atmospheric breathing motion.
- Keep transition logic, but cap T2/T3/T4 transitions at 800ms total.

---

## 10. Responsive Pacing

Mobile users scroll **faster**. The page must compensate:
- Mobile chapter total scroll height: **70%** of equivalent desktop height.
- Mobile holds (silence scenes): **40vh** (vs 50vh desktop).
- Mobile reveal staggers: tighter (`STAGGER.tight` instead of `editorial`).

This is not a bug — it is the **mobile cut** of the same chapter.

---

## 11. Implementation Standards

### Tailwind v4
- Define breakpoints in `app/globals.css` `@theme` block:
  ```css
  @theme {
    --breakpoint-xs: 0;
    --breakpoint-sm: 480px;
    --breakpoint-md: 768px;
    --breakpoint-lg: 1024px;
    --breakpoint-xl: 1280px;
    --breakpoint-2xl: 1536px;
    --breakpoint-3xl: 1920px;
  }
  ```
- Use Tailwind utilities (`md:`, `lg:`, `xl:`) for layout. Use CSS custom properties for tokens.

### Hooks
- `useBreakpoint()` — returns the current breakpoint name (debounced on resize).
- `useIsTouch()` — returns `true` if `(pointer: coarse)` matches.
- `useReducedMotion()` — global flag.

### Patterns
- Use `gsap.matchMedia()` to register/clean GSAP timelines per breakpoint.
- Use Next.js `<Image>` `sizes` attribute correctly per breakpoint to avoid over-fetching.
- Test every chapter at exactly: 360px, 768px, 1024px, 1440px, 1920px.

---

## 12. DO / DON'T

### DO
- DO build mobile-first; enrich at desktop.
- DO degrade motion progressively across breakpoints.
- DO convert horizontal storytelling to vertical on mobile.
- DO honor `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce` globally.
- DO test every chapter at the 5 canonical widths.

### DON'T
- DON'T preserve horizontal scroll on touch.
- DON'T use hover-only content on touch devices.
- DON'T ship custom cursors or magnetic effects on touch.
- DON'T let display type wrap into more than 3 lines on mobile.
- DON'T match desktop scroll length on mobile — adapt the cut.

---

## 13. Cinematic Rationale

- A theatrical cut is shorter than the director's cut, but both move the audience. Mobile is the same idea — fewer effects, same emotional arc.
- Touch users are not "lesser" users. They are an audience watching the same film on a smaller screen. The film must still play.
- Reduced motion is not a degradation — it is a **respectful adaptation**. The audience told us how they want to watch; we comply.
